# ─── FULL REFERENCE — every image.env option, annotated ────────────
# This is the COMPLETE option set. For a new repo, start from the slim
# image.env.example and copy the extra lines you need across from here:
#   cp image.env.example  image.env  &&  $EDITOR image.env
#   cp inject-certs.sh install-ca-certificates.sh certs/ .   # vendor
#
# Neither this file nor image.env.example is ever sourced — the live
# image.env is what build.sh consumes. Keep SECRETS OUT of image.env;
# pass tokens via masked CI variables. Precedence: shell / CI > image.env.
# ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# UPSTREAM
# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# Pushed tag = <UPSTREAM_TAG>-<gitShort>, e.g. nginx:1.25.3-alpine-a1b2c3d.
# Each push backend prepends its own host/project to <IMAGE_NAME>:<tag>.

# ── Image identity (one full image URL) ────────────────────────────
# ONE line carries registry + repo path + :tag. build.sh splits it into
# its parts automatically, and Renovate reads the repo + tag straight
# out of this URL — NO separate `# renovate:` hint comment to maintain.
# Renovate opens a chore(deps) MR whenever a newer tag ships upstream.
# Forms that all decompose correctly:
#   docker.io/library/nginx:1.25.3-alpine        Docker Hub official
#   ghcr.io/org/app:1.4.2                         GHCR (any registry)
#   registry.example.com:5000/team/app:2.0        private registry + port
#   nginx:1.25.3-alpine                           shorthand → docker.io/library/nginx
# A pinned @sha256:... digest is accepted but informational only — the
# base digest is always re-resolved fresh at build time.
UPSTREAM_REF="docker.io/library/nginx:1.25.3-alpine"

# ── Per-segment overrides (rarely needed) ──────────────────────────
# All three are normally derived from UPSTREAM_REF above. Uncomment one
# ONLY to override what the splitter produced — e.g. pull through an
# air-gapped mirror host while keeping UPSTREAM_REF pointed at the
# public repo so Renovate still tracks upstream. A value set here wins.
# UPSTREAM_REGISTRY="docker.io/library"
# UPSTREAM_IMAGE="nginx"
# UPSTREAM_TAG="1.25.3-alpine"

# ── Upstream PULL authentication (explicit-wins, safe fallback) ─────
# Auth for pulling the BASE image is decoupled from the push side and
# resolves in this order:
#   1. UPSTREAM_REGISTRY_USER + UPSTREAM_REGISTRY_PASSWORD (below) —
#      used for ANY upstream host. Set these for a Docker Hub / ghcr /
#      quay account, or a private mirror with its own credentials.
#   2. else ARTIFACTORY_USER + ARTIFACTORY_TOKEN/PASSWORD — used
#      AUTOMATICALLY, but ONLY when the upstream host is in the same
#      domain as ARTIFACTORY_URL (i.e. the upstream IS your Artifactory
#      mirror). So if you pull through your own Artifactory you need set
#      NOTHING here — it just works.
#   3. else anonymous pull (public / anonymous-pull registries).
# Artifactory credentials are NEVER sent to a public registry.
# UPSTREAM_REGISTRY_PASSWORD accepts a password OR a token. Keep the
# password/token OUT of this file — pass it as a masked CI variable.
# UPSTREAM_REGISTRY_USER="<upstream-pull-user>"
# UPSTREAM_REGISTRY_PASSWORD="<upstream-pull-token>"   # mask in CI

# ── Pushed-name override ────────────────────────────────────────────
# IMAGE_NAME defaults to the LEAF of UPSTREAM_IMAGE — "prom/prometheus"
# → "prometheus" with no override needed. Set this only for a custom
# short name like "nginx-hardened".
# IMAGE_NAME="nginx-hardened"

# ── Tag-suffix toggle ───────────────────────────────────────────────
# Append git short SHA to the pushed tag. Default true (build
# differentiation matters when rebuilding the same upstream tag).
# Set false for moving aliases like "latest" — WARNING: subsequent
# builds then OVERWRITE the same tag.
# Falsy values: false / 0 / no / off (case-insensitive).
# APPEND_GIT_SHORT="true"

# ── OCI labels ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────
VENDOR="example.com"
# AUTHORS="Platform Engineering"

# ── Upstream USER override (almost never needed) ────────────────────
# build.sh auto-detects via `crane config <upstream>` and passes as a
# build-arg. Set manually only to force a different USER than what
# the upstream image declares.
# ORIGINAL_USER="root"

# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# CUSTOMISATION — happens in the Dockerfile, not here
# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# CVE remediation, extra packages, config drops, HEALTHCHECK etc. go
# in the Dockerfile's marked FORK EDITS region. image.env only carries
# behavioural toggles.
#
# Cert injection is automatic: drop *.crt into certs/ (or set CA_CERT
# as a CI var with PEM content) and the cert sidecar picks them up.

# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# PUSH BACKEND SELECTOR
# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# Resolves to scripts/push-backends/<value>.sh. Each backend reads
# its OWN namespace — they never cross-derive. Set ONLY the matching
# section below.
#   "harbor"      → harbor.sh       (reads HARBOR_*)
#   "artifactory_jcr" → artifactory_jcr.sh (Free)
#   "artifactory_pro" → artifactory_pro.sh (Pro)
# REGISTRY_KIND="harbor"

# ── HARBOR (when REGISTRY_KIND="harbor") ───────────────────────────
# Push URL = <HARBOR_REGISTRY>/<HARBOR_PROJECT>/<IMAGE_NAME>:<TAG>.
# HARBOR_PROJECT shape (pick one, stick to it):
#   "apps/platform"   per-image-class with RBAC subdir
#   "dev" / "prod"    per-environment (promote = copy by digest)
#   "library"         single shared project, tiny orgs
# HARBOR_REGISTRY="harbor.example.com"
# HARBOR_PROJECT="apps/platform"
# HARBOR_USER="svc-cicd"
# HARBOR_PASSWORD="<harbor-cli-secret-or-robot-token>"   # mask in CI

# ── ARTIFACTORY (when REGISTRY_KIND="artifactory_jcr" or "artifactory_pro") ─
# The backend file is selected by REGISTRY_KIND directly:
#   "artifactory_jcr" → push-backends/artifactory_jcr.sh — Free tier
#                       (uses plain docker push + manual build-info
#                       reconstruction via scripts/lib/build-info-merge.py
#                       — needs python3 on the runner)
#   "artifactory_pro" → push-backends/artifactory_pro.sh — Pro tier
#                       (jf docker push native build-info + optional
#                       jf docker scan / jf build-scan; no python3
#                       dependency, no manifest-merger helper)
#
# Pro-only repos can delete scripts/push-backends/artifactory_jcr.sh +
# scripts/lib/build-info-merge.py and the Pro path still works.

# ── Required ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# ARTIFACTORY_URL="https://artifactory.example.com"   # Cloud: https://<org>.jfrog.io
#
# ARTIFACTORY_USER must match the username in the access token's
# `sub` claim, NOT the login email — JFrog Cloud's docker-login
# rejects email form. Find it:
#   echo "$TOKEN" | cut -d. -f2 | base64 -d 2>/dev/null | jq -r .sub
# ARTIFACTORY_USER="svc-cicd"
#
# Token preferred; password works if tokens aren't available.
# ARTIFACTORY_TOKEN="<your-jfrog-access-token>"        # mask in CI
# ARTIFACTORY_PASSWORD="<svc-cicd-password>"           # mask in CI
#
# Lowercase / digits / dashes only on JFrog Cloud.
# ARTIFACTORY_TEAM="platform"

# ── Pro tier ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# ARTIFACTORY_PRO is now auto-set by the backend you chose via
# REGISTRY_KIND — no need to set it here.
# ARTIFACTORY_PROJECT="platform"               # default: ARTIFACTORY_TEAM

# ── Optional ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# ARTIFACTORY_ENVIRONMENT="dev"                # "prod" → prod repo suffix
# ARTIFACTORY_PUSH_HOST="docker.artifactory.example.com"  # default: host of ARTIFACTORY_URL
# ARTIFACTORY_BUILD_NAME="nginx-build"         # default: ${IMAGE_NAME}-build
# ARTIFACTORY_BUILD_NUMBER="2026.05.12-01"     # default: CI_JOB_ID / CI_PIPELINE_ID / etc.
# ARTIFACTORY_PROPERTIES="security.scan=pending;approval.status=draft"

# ── Inline Xray scans (Pro-only, opt-in, default OFF) ──────────────
# Run INSIDE the push backend (build job), as opposed to the
# standalone scripts/scan/xray-{vuln,sbom}.sh which are separate CI
# stages. The ARTIFACTORY_BUILD_* var names reflect "runs inside the
# build job" — not a separate build step.
# ARTIFACTORY_BUILD_XRAY_PRESCAN="false"      # jf docker scan BEFORE push
# ARTIFACTORY_BUILD_XRAY_POSTSCAN="false"     # jf build-scan AFTER push
# ARTIFACTORY_XRAY_FAIL_ON_VIOLATIONS="false" # "true" → exit 1 on violation

# ── Layout templates ───────────────────────────────────────────────
# Two templates resolve the docker push URL + REST storage path.
# Placeholders: ${ARTIFACTORY_PUSH_HOST}, ${ARTIFACTORY_TEAM},
# ${ARTIFACTORY_ENVIRONMENT}, ${ARTIFACTORY_REPO_SUFFIX} (dev→local,
# prod→prod), ${IMAGE_NAME}, ${IMAGE_TAG}.
#
# In GitLab CI variables, set raw=true so GitLab doesn't expand the
# ${...} at injection time.
#
# Six layout presets — uncomment ONE pair (or leave both unset for
# Layout A's defaults).
#
# IMPORTANT — JFrog Cloud SaaS vs self-hosted:
#   - JFrog Cloud SaaS (https://<org>.jfrog.io) is SINGLE-DOMAIN with
#     no docker subdomains. You MUST use Layout F (path-based).
#     Layouts C/D/E reference docker.<host> / <team>.<host> subdomains
#     that only work on self-hosted Pro with custom DNS — pointing
#     them at *.jfrog.io just returns 302s to JFrog's landing page.
#   - Self-hosted Artifactory Pro can use any layout, depending on
#     how your platform team configured DNS + reverse proxy.

# ── Layout A: Per-team repos (default fallback) ─────────────────────
#   Docker push:  <host>/<team>/<image>:<tag>
#   Storage:      <team>-docker-<suffix>/<image>/<tag>/manifest.json
# ARTIFACTORY_IMAGE_REF='${ARTIFACTORY_PUSH_HOST}/${ARTIFACTORY_TEAM}/${IMAGE_NAME}:${IMAGE_TAG}'
# ARTIFACTORY_MANIFEST_PATH='${ARTIFACTORY_TEAM}-docker-${ARTIFACTORY_REPO_SUFFIX}/${IMAGE_NAME}/${IMAGE_TAG}/manifest.json'

# ── Layout B: Shared repo with team subfolder ───────────────────────
#   Docker push:  <host>/docker/<team>/<image>:<tag>
#   Storage:      docker/<team>/<image>/<tag>/manifest.json
# ARTIFACTORY_IMAGE_REF='${ARTIFACTORY_PUSH_HOST}/docker/${ARTIFACTORY_TEAM}/${IMAGE_NAME}:${IMAGE_TAG}'
# ARTIFACTORY_MANIFEST_PATH='docker/${ARTIFACTORY_TEAM}/${IMAGE_NAME}/${IMAGE_TAG}/manifest.json'

# ── Layout C: Subdomain-routed shared repo (JFrog recommended) ──────
#   Docker push:  docker.<host>/<team>/<image>:<tag>
#   Storage:      docker/<team>/<image>/<tag>/manifest.json
# ARTIFACTORY_PUSH_HOST="docker.artifactory.example.com"
# ARTIFACTORY_IMAGE_REF='${ARTIFACTORY_PUSH_HOST}/${ARTIFACTORY_TEAM}/${IMAGE_NAME}:${IMAGE_TAG}'
# ARTIFACTORY_MANIFEST_PATH='docker/${ARTIFACTORY_TEAM}/${IMAGE_NAME}/${IMAGE_TAG}/manifest.json'

# ── Layout D: Subdomain-per-team ────────────────────────────────────
#   Docker push:  <team>.<host>/<image>:<tag>
#   Storage:      <team>-docker-<suffix>/<image>/<tag>/manifest.json
# ARTIFACTORY_PUSH_HOST='${ARTIFACTORY_TEAM}.artifactory.example.com'
# ARTIFACTORY_IMAGE_REF='${ARTIFACTORY_PUSH_HOST}/${IMAGE_NAME}:${IMAGE_TAG}'
# ARTIFACTORY_MANIFEST_PATH='${ARTIFACTORY_TEAM}-docker-${ARTIFACTORY_REPO_SUFFIX}/${IMAGE_NAME}/${IMAGE_TAG}/manifest.json'

# ── Layout E: Team-dispatch subdomain (needs external nginx map) ────
#   Docker push:  docker.<host>/<team>/<image>:<tag>
#   Storage:      <team>-docker-<suffix>/<image>/<tag>/manifest.json
# ARTIFACTORY_PUSH_HOST="docker.artifactory.example.com"
# ARTIFACTORY_IMAGE_REF='${ARTIFACTORY_PUSH_HOST}/${ARTIFACTORY_TEAM}/${IMAGE_NAME}:${IMAGE_TAG}'
# ARTIFACTORY_MANIFEST_PATH='${ARTIFACTORY_TEAM}-docker-${ARTIFACTORY_REPO_SUFFIX}/${IMAGE_NAME}/${IMAGE_TAG}/manifest.json'

# ── Layout F: JFrog Cloud SaaS or Pro single-domain (path-based) ────
#   Docker push:  <host>/<repo>/<image>:<tag>
#   Storage:      <repo>/<image>/<tag>/manifest.json
# Canonical layout for JFrog Cloud — single domain, no subdomains.
# Also works on self-hosted Pro without a subdomain reverse proxy.
# Validated against an <org>.jfrog.io Cloud trial with a path-based
# docker repo.
# ARTIFACTORY_PUSH_HOST="yourorg.jfrog.io"
# ARTIFACTORY_IMAGE_REF='${ARTIFACTORY_PUSH_HOST}/<repo>/${IMAGE_NAME}:${IMAGE_TAG}'
# ARTIFACTORY_MANIFEST_PATH='<repo>/${IMAGE_NAME}/${IMAGE_TAG}/manifest.json'

# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# SCAN-SIDE ARTIFACTORY OVERRIDES
# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# Push and scan can target different Artifactory instances. Useful
# when pushing to JCR Free but scanning via a separate Pro/Cloud
# trial with an Xray licence.

# ── Separate Xray instance (unset = use push-side creds) ────────────
# XRAY_ARTIFACTORY_URL="https://yourorg.jfrog.io"
# XRAY_ARTIFACTORY_USER="svc-xray"
# XRAY_ARTIFACTORY_TOKEN="<your-jfrog-access-token>"     # mask in CI
# XRAY_ARTIFACTORY_PASSWORD="<svc-xray-password>"        # mask in CI

# ── SBOM generation toggle ──────────────────────────────────────────
# Generate a CycloneDX SBOM via a second `jf docker scan` call.
# Default ON. Set false when Syft / Trivy already produces the SBOM.
# XRAY_GENERATE_SBOM="true"

# ── Scan target override ────────────────────────────────────────────
# Override the scan target for xray-vuln.sh / xray-sbom.sh. Default
# resolution: $1 > XRAY_SCAN_REF > IMAGE_DIGEST > IMAGE_REF > UPSTREAM_REF.
# XRAY_SCAN_REF="docker.io/library/nginx:1.25.3-alpine"
# XRAY_SCAN_FORMAT="simple-json"      # alt: "json" (raw Xray API shape)

# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# SEVERITY GATES (opt-in — exit 2 on violation, blocks the job)
# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# Comma-separated. Case differs per tool — copy exactly as shown.
# XRAY_FAIL_ON_SEVERITY="critical,high"
# GRYPE_FAIL_ON_SEVERITY="Critical,High"
# TRIVY_FAIL_ON_SEVERITY="CRITICAL,HIGH"

# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# TOOL INSTALL URLS  (air-gap support)
# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# Each scan / build script auto-installs its tool from the URL below
# if the binary isn't already on PATH. Defaults reach public GitHub
# releases — override these to point at your internal Artifactory
# mirror when air-gapped.
#
# Tool versions: leave empty to use the script's built-in default
# (one source of truth — bump the version in the script itself).
# Override here only when pinning to a specific version per fork.

# ── crane (go-containerregistry — image digest + retag) ─────────────
# Used by build.sh for base.digest resolution + retag-and-push.
# CRANE_URL="https://artifactory.example.com/artifactory/generic-tools/crane/v0.20.2/go-containerregistry_Linux_x86_64.tar.gz"

# ── Syft (Anchore — SBOM emitter) ───────────────────────────────────
# Used by scripts/scan/syft-sbom.sh. SYFT_INSTALLER_URL accepts either the
# upstream .sh installer OR a syft release .tar.gz/.tgz (auto-detected by
# suffix) — point it at an Artifactory-mirrored tarball for air-gapped runners.
# SYFT_INSTALLER_URL="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/anchore/syft/main/install.sh"
# SYFT_VERSION=""           # default v1.45.1 in scripts/scan/syft-sbom.sh (.sh installer only)

# ── Grype (Anchore — vuln scanner) ──────────────────────────────────
# Used by scripts/scan/grype-vuln.sh. GRYPE_INSTALLER_URL accepts either the
# upstream .sh installer OR a grype release .tar.gz/.tgz (auto-detected by
# suffix) — point it at an Artifactory-mirrored tarball for air-gapped runners.
# GRYPE_INSTALLER_URL="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/anchore/grype/main/install.sh"
# GRYPE_VERSION=""          # default v0.114.0 in scripts/scan/grype-vuln.sh (.sh installer only)

# ── JFrog CLI (sudoless, REQUIRED for Artifactory backend) ──────────
# Set ONE of the three URLs to a file in your local Artifactory.
# None set = build fails with a clear error. All three install to
# ${JF_INSTALL_DIR:-$HOME/.local/bin}.
JF_BINARY_URL="https://artifactory.example.com/artifactory/jfrog-releases-remote/jfrog-cli/v2-jf/2.103.0/jfrog-cli-linux-amd64/jf"
# JF_DEB_URL="https://artifactory.example.com/artifactory/jfrog-debs/pool/jfrog-cli-v2-jf_2.103.0_amd64.deb"
# JF_RPM_URL="https://artifactory.example.com/artifactory/jfrog-rpms/jfrog-cli-v2-jf-2.103.0.x86_64.rpm"
# JF_INSTALL_DIR="${HOME}/.local/bin"

# ── Cert sidecar base image ─────────────────────────────────────────
# Shell-bearing builder used to prepare the trust store (works on
# distroless / chainguard / scratch upstreams too). Default alpine.
# For air-gap, point at a pre-baked image hosted internally that
# ALREADY contains ca-certificates + your corp CA pre-trusted. See
# README "Closed-network / air-gap" for the bootstrap-Dockerfile pattern.
# CERT_BUILDER_IMAGE="docker.io/library/alpine:3.20"

# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# SBOM SINKS (scripts/ingest/sbom-post.sh — all opt-in, no-op when unset)
# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# 5 sinks ship the canonical sbom.cdx.json. Mix and match — set as
# many as apply. Sinks are independent: configuring one doesn't
# require any of the others.

# ── Sink 1: Generic CycloneDX webhook ───────────────────────────────
# Any POST endpoint that accepts a CycloneDX JSON body.
# SBOM_WEBHOOK_URL="https://sbom-collector.example.com/api/sbom"
# SBOM_WEBHOOK_AUTH_HEADER="Authorization: Bearer <token>"   # mask in CI

# ── Sink 2: OWASP Dependency-Track ──────────────────────────────────
# CVE correlation + notification. Auto-creates the project on first upload
# (uploads via PUT /api/v1/bom — DT's JSON path; POST is multipart-only).
# DEPENDENCY_TRACK_URL must be DT's API server (not the SPA host).
# DEPENDENCY_TRACK_URL="https://dtrack-api.example.com"
# DEPENDENCY_TRACK_API_KEY="<dt-api-key>"        # mask in CI; team needs BOM_UPLOAD
# DEPENDENCY_TRACK_PROJECT="my-image"
#
# Git provenance into DT (all best-effort, three channels DT actually keeps):
#   • project VERSION = IMAGE_TAG (<upstream>-<gitShort>) — per-commit history.
#   • metadata.component.externalReferences (vcs+distribution) → "External
#     References" tab. The vcs URL defaults to `git remote origin`; override:
# DT_VCS_URL="https://git.example.com/team/repo"
#   • project Properties (newen/: git_commit, scanned_image, image_digest,
#     image_tag, build_pipeline) → "Properties" tab. Requires the API key's
#     team to hold PORTFOLIO_MANAGEMENT; without it, this step is skipped
#     (version + external references still apply). Pipeline label override:
# DT_BUILD_PIPELINE="my-pipeline"           # default: CI_PROJECT_PATH or template name

# ── Sink 3: Artifactory generic repo, Xray-indexed ──────────────────
# Auto-scans on upload (Xray watches the repo). Uses ARTIFACTORY_URL/
# USER/TOKEN. Path: <repo>/<image>/<tag>/sbom.cdx.json
# ARTIFACTORY_SBOM_REPO="sboms-local"

# ── Sink 4: Artifactory generic repo, plain archive ─────────────────
# No Xray expectation — just a long-term browsable archive. Use
# alongside Sink 3 when you want both an indexed scan AND a cross-
# team browsable archive of the same SBOMs.
# ARTIFACTORY_SBOM_ARCHIVE_REPO="<team>-generic-<env>-local"

# ── Sink 5: Splunk HTTP Event Collector (audit trail) ───────────────
# Shared with VULN SINKS below — same HEC URL/token, different
# sourcetype per artifact type.
# SPLUNK_HEC_URL="https://splunk.example.com:8088"
# SPLUNK_HEC_TOKEN="<your-splunk-hec-uuid>"      # mask in CI
# SPLUNK_HEC_INDEX="security"                    # default: main
# SPLUNK_SBOM_SOURCETYPE="cyclonedx:json"        # SBOM events
# SPLUNK_HEC_INSECURE="false"                    # "true" → curl -k
# SPLUNK_SOURCE="pipeline"                       # → "pipeline-job"

# ── Inline post toggles (scan-time hand-off to *-post.sh) ──────────
# By default, sink shipping happens in the dedicated ingest stages
# (sbom-ingest + vuln-ingest). Set these to "true" to ALSO hand off
# from the scan job itself for faster delivery (mirrors Xray's native
# scan+post pattern). Result: artifact ships twice — once inline,
# once via ingest stage. Useful for fail-fast SecOps alerting.
#
# Xray scanners default to TRUE (preserve native behaviour). Syft +
# Grype + Trivy default to FALSE (rely on ingest stage).
# SBOM_INLINE_POST="false"
# VULN_INLINE_POST="false"

# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# VULN SINKS (scripts/ingest/vuln-post.sh — all opt-in, no-op when unset)
# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# 3 sinks ship the canonical vuln-scan.json. Mirrors SBOM sinks —
# scanner-agnostic (auto-detects grype / trivy / xray from report
# shape and picks a sensible Splunk sourcetype).

# ── Sink 1: Generic vuln webhook ────────────────────────────────────
# Any POST endpoint that accepts the raw vuln-scan.json body.
# VULN_WEBHOOK_URL="https://vuln-collector.example.com/api/scan"
# VULN_WEBHOOK_AUTH_HEADER="Authorization: Bearer <token>"   # mask in CI

# ── Sink 2: Artifactory generic archive (long-term browsable copy) ──
# PUT to <repo>/<image>/<tag>/vuln-scan.json. Uses ARTIFACTORY_URL/
# USER/TOKEN from the ARTIFACTORY backend section. No Xray indexing
# required — just a stable URL for auditors / SecOps to fetch later.
# ARTIFACTORY_VULN_ARCHIVE_REPO="<team>-generic-<env>-local"

# ── Sink 3: Splunk HTTP Event Collector (audit trail) ───────────────
# Reuses SPLUNK_HEC_URL + SPLUNK_HEC_TOKEN + SPLUNK_HEC_INDEX from
# the SBOM SINKS section above. Default sourcetype is auto-picked
# from the report shape — override here only when needed.
# VULN_SPLUNK_SOURCETYPE="security:vuln:scan"  # default: scanner-specific
#                                              #   grype → anchore:grype:vuln
#                                              #   trivy → aqua:trivy:vuln
#                                              #   xray  → jfrog:xray:scan

# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# CANONICAL ARTIFACT FILENAMES  (overrides — almost never needed)
# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# Defaults from scripts/lib/artifact-names.sh. Override only if
# running multiple producers in one job context (otherwise they collide).
# SBOM_FILE="sbom.cdx.json"
# VULN_SCAN_FILE="vuln-scan.json"
# SBOM_TARGET="image"                            # "source" → syft scans dir:${PROJECT_ROOT}

# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# GRYPE OPTIONS
# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# Air-gap CVE DB mirror. Set ARTIFACTORY_GRYPE_DB_REPO to mirror
# Anchore's DB into a generic repo; grype-vuln.sh fetches from there.
# ARTIFACTORY_GRYPE_DB_REPO="grype-db-local"
# GRYPE_DB_MIRROR_SUBPATH="grype-db/v6"          # default

# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# TRIVY  (OPT-IN — off by default behind the ALLOW_TRIVY kill-switch)
# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# Trivy scan scripts are gated by ALLOW_TRIVY (default 0 = off). Flip
# the toggle to run Trivy — set it here, as a CI/CD variable, or as an
# env var; no script edit needed. The version is pinned in
# scripts/scan/trivy-{vuln,sbom}.sh (default 0.69.3) and the scripts
# HARD-FAIL v0.69.4–v0.69.6 (compromised range) even if a mirror serves
# them. (You also need the matching trivy-* CI jobs enabled.)
# ALLOW_TRIVY="1"
# TRIVY_VERSION=""
# TRIVY_INSTALLER_URL="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/aquasecurity/trivy/main/contrib/install.sh"
# TRIVY_BINARY_URL="https://artifactory.example.com/artifactory/generic-tools/trivy/0.69.3/trivy_0.69.3_Linux-64bit.tar.gz"

# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# DEBUG
# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# Verbose [debug] decision logs from every script that sources
# scripts/lib/load-image-env.sh. Off by default.
# BUILD_DEBUG="false"

# load_image_env's per-var dump mode:
#   true (default)  per-var listing with [source] annotation
#   summary         one-line count: "Loaded N vars (M shell-overridden)"
#   false           silent
# Secrets are always redacted.
# LOAD_ENV_LOG="true"
